SIMPLE: trim
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trim
<hw>Trim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trimmed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trimming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>trimen</ets>,
<ets>trumen</ets>, AS. <ets>trymian</ets>, <ets>trymman</ets>, to
prepare, dispose, make strong, fr. <ets>trum</ets> firm, strong; of
uncertain origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make trim; to put in due
order for any purpose; to make right, neat, or pleasing; to
adjust.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hermit <qex>trimmed</qex> his little fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dress; to decorate; to adorn; to invest; to
embellish; <as>as, to <ex>trim</ex> a hat</as>.</def> <-- to
<ex>trim</ex> a Christmas tree. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A rotten building newly <qex>trimmed</qex> over.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was <qex>trimmed</qex> in Julia's gown.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make ready or right by cutting or shortening; to
clip or lop; to curtail; <as>as, to <ex>trim</ex> the hair; to
<ex>trim</ex> a tree</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ And <xex>trimmed</xex> the
cheerful lamp.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>To dress, as timber; to make
smooth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To adjust, as a
ship, by arranging the cargo, or disposing the weight of persons or
goods, so equally on each side of the center and at each end, that she
shall sit well on the water and sail well; <as>as, to <ex>trim</ex> a
ship, or a boat</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To arrange in due order
for sailing; <as>as, to <ex>trim</ex> the sails</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To rebuke; to reprove; also, to beat.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To trim in</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>to fit, as a
piece of timber, into other work.</cd> -- <col><b>To trim up</b></col>,
<cd>to dress; to put in order.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I found her <qex>trimming up</qex> the diadem⟦br⟧
On her dead mistress.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trim
<hw>Trim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To balance; to
fluctuate between parties, so as to appear to favor each.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trim
<hw>Trim</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Dress; gear;
ornaments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seeing him just pass the window in his woodland
<qex>trim</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Order; disposition; condition; <as>as, to be in good
<ex>trim</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ The <xex>trim</xex> of an
encounter.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of a ship or her cargo, ballast, masts,
etc., by which she is well prepared for sailing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arch)</fld> <def>The lighter woodwork in the
interior of a building; especially, that used around openings, generally
in the form of a molded architrave, to protect the plastering at those
points.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In ballast trim</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>having
only ballast on board.</cd> <au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au> -- <col><b>Trim of
the masts</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>their position in regard to
the ship and to each other, as near or distant, far forward or much aft,
erect or raking.</cd> -- <col><b>Trim of sails</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>that adjustment, with reference to the wind,
witch is best adapted to impel the ship forward.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Trim
<hw>Trim</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Trimmer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Trimmest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[See <er>Trim</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Fitly adjusted; being in good order., or made ready
for service or use; firm; compact; snug; neat; fair; <as>as, the ship is
<ex>trim</ex>, or <ex>trim</ex> built; everything about the man is
<ex>trim</ex>; a person is <ex>trim</ex> when his body is well shaped
and firm; his dress is <ex>trim</ex> when it fits closely to his body,
and appears tight and snug; a man or a soldier is <ex>trim</ex> when he
stands erect.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With comely carriage of her countenance <qex>trim</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So deemed I till I viewed their <qex>trim</qex> array⟦br⟧
Of boats last night.</q> <rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trimaculated</ent>⟦br⟧
